org.modelio.vcore.smkernel

Class SmObjectImpl

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.modelio.vcore.smkernel.SmObjectImpl
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Comparable<MObject>, org.eclipse.emf.common.notify.Notifier, org.eclipse.emf.ecore.EObject, ISmMeta, ISmStorable, MObject

    public abstract class SmObjectImpl
extends Object
implements ISmMeta, ISmStorable, MObject, Serializable, org.eclipse.emf.ecore.EObject
    SmObjectImpl instances are the objects that are managed by smkernel along with SmObjectData.

    A SmObjectImpl holds a Java weak reference to its SmObjectData data structure. Therefore data can be garbaged at any moment. Before being garbaged, data are in fact swapped to the disk for future re-use by a data cache holder defined in the upper level.

    SmObjectImpl features cover different areas, each area is covered by a specific interface that SmObjectImpl currently implements:

    • semantic features management (attributes and dependencies) defined by ISmMeta
    • storage management covered by ISmStorable
    • methods for external programmers manipulating the model objects at the meta level defined by MObject
    • EMF EObject methods for EMF compatibility

      • isShell

        public boolean isShell()
        Description copied from interface: MObject
        Tells whether the object is an unresolved reference.

        A shell object is an object that is not present in any known repository but is referenced in another one.

        A shell object has the following behavior:

        • A shell object is not modifiable. Trying to modify it will result in an exception.
        • Only the name of the object has a significant value.
        • Other attributes have a default value and dependencies are empty.
        Browsing a shell object will return empty collections.
        Specified by:
        isShell in interface MObject
        Returns:
        true if the object is unresolved, else false.

      • isDeleted

        public boolean isDeleted()
        Description copied from interface: MObject
        Tells whether the element is deleted in the model.

        A deleted object has the following behavior:

        • A deleted object is not modifiable. Trying to modify it will result in an exception.
        • The object attributes are still readable.
        • A deleted object is not visible from its non deleted owner and references, but the deleted object dependencies are still browsable.
        Specified by:
        isDeleted in interface MObject
        Returns:
        true if the element is deleted, else false.
        See Also:
        MObject.isShell(), MObject.isValid()

      • appendDepVal

        public boolean appendDepVal(SmDependency dep,
                            SmObjectImpl value,
                            int index)

        Idem que la methode appendDependency, mais a? partir de la dependance (sans verification du nom de la dependance).
        Cette methode permet d'ajouter une dependance. Si un meta-objet est associe a? l'objet courant la methode passe la main au meta-objet.
        Exemple:
        SmObject *dep; SmObject *obj;
        obj.appendDepVal(ProjectDefinedDomain(),dep);
        Les anomalies:
        Type mismatch: Si l'objet n'est pas de type attendu.

      • toString

        public String toString()
        Dumps the object name, UUID and metaclass.

        May dump flag strings:

        • DEAD : the object has no more data, the data is not in swap either. This object is not usable anymore and should not be used naymore
        • Shell : the object is an unresolved reference or its loading partially failed. isShell() returns true.
        • Deleted : The object is deleted but still readable. isDeleted() returns true.
        In case of exception loading the name the exception string is dumped instead of the name so that this method should never fail even for a broken object.
        Overrides:
        toString in class Object
